org.jtuples

Class Tuples

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jtuples.Tuples

  • public final class Tuples
extends Object
    This class consists exclusively of static methods that return or operate on tuples. It contains some factory methods as well as methods for the following operations:
    • flatRight and flatLeft
    • associateRight and associateLeft
    • map
    • zip
    Author:
    Andre Santos, Benjamim Sonntag
    See Also:
    Tuple

      • flatFirst

        public static <A,B,C> Triple<A,B,C> flatFirst(Pair<Pair<A,B>,C> pair)
        Flattens a nested tuple. The resulting tuple will contain all the previous elements in the same order. For example, for a pair ((a, b), c) the result is the triple (a, b, c).
        Type Parameters:
        A - the type of the first element of the inner pair
        B - the type of the second element of the inner pair
        C - the type of the second element of the outer pair
        Parameters:
        pair - a pair that has another pair in the first position
        Returns:
        a triple
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if the given pair is null or if the inner pair is null

      • associateFirst

        public static <A,B,C> Pair<Pair<A,B>,C> associateFirst(Pair<A,Pair<B,C>> pair)
        Associates a nested tuple on the first position. This takes a pair with a nesting in the second member and returns a tuple that contains all the previous elements in the same order, but with the nesting in the first position. For example, for a pair (a, (b, c)) the result is the pair ((a, b), c).
        Type Parameters:
        A - the type of the first element of the outer pair
        B - the type of the first element of the inner pair
        C - the type of the second element of the inner pair
        Parameters:
        pair - a pair that has another pair in the second position
        Returns:
        a pair that has another pair on the first position
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if the given pair is null or if the inner pair is null

      • associateSecond

        Associates a nested tuple on the second position. This takes a pair with a nesting in the second member and returns a tuple that contains all the previous elements in the same order, but with the nesting in the first position. For example, for a pair (a, (b, c)) the result is the pair ((a, b), c).
        Type Parameters:
        A - the type of the first element of the inner pair
        B - the type of the second element of the inner pair

        Parameters:

      • map

        public static <A,B> Pair<B,B> map(Pair<? extends A,? extends A> pair,
                                  Function<A,B> f)
        Creates a pair by applying a function to each element of the given pair. The resulting pair's elements will be the result of applying the function to each element of the given pair, in order. That is, for a function fn and a pair (a, b) the result is the pair (fn(a), fn(b)).
        Type Parameters:
        A - the type of the elements of the given pair
        B - the type of the elements of the resulting pair
        Parameters:
        pair - a pair whose elements have a common superclass
        f - a function to be applied to all elements of pair
        Returns:
        a pair whose elements are the result of applying f to all elements of the given pair
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if the given pair is null or if the given function is null

      • map

                                      Function<A,B> f)
        Creates a triple by applying a function to each element of the given triple. The resulting triple's elements will be the result of applying the function to each element of the given triple, in order.         public static <A,B> Decuple<B,B,B,B,B,B,B,B,B,B> map(Decuple<? extends A,? extends A,? extends A,? extends A,? extends A,? extends A,? extends A,? extends A,? extends A,? extends A> decuple,
                                                     Function<A,B> f)
        Creates a decuple by applying a function to each element of the given decuple. The resulting decuple's elements will be the result of applying the function to each element of the given decuple, in order. That is, for a function fn and a decuple (a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, i, j) the result is the decuple (fn(a), fn(b), fn(c), fn(d), fn(e), fn(f), fn(g), fn(h), fn(i), fn(j)).
        Type Parameters:
        A - the type of the elements of the given decuple
        B - the type of the elements of the resulting decuple
        Parameters:
        decuple - a decuple whose elements have a common superclass
        f - a function to be applied to all elements of decuple
        Returns:
        a decuple whose elements are the result of applying f to all elements of the given decuple
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if the given decuple is null or if the given function is null

      • zip

        public static <A,B> Collection<Pair<A,B>> zip(Iterable<A> firsts,
                                              Iterable<B> seconds)
        Zips the given iterables into a collection of pairs. The resulting collection will contain pairs of all the previous elements, preserving order, and stopping at the size of the smallest of the iterators. That is, for lists [a, b, c] and [d, e, f, g] the result is the list of pairs [(a, d), (b, e), (c, f)].
        Type Parameters:
        A - the type of the elements of the first iterable
        B - the type of the elements of the second iterable
        Parameters:
        firsts - the elements to place on the first position of each pair
        seconds - the elements to place on the second position of each pair
        Returns:
        a collection of pairs
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if any of the iterables is null
